Introduction

This is a data set over the various game rankings for PlayStation, Xbox, Wii, and PC with sales over 100,000 copies. I have constrained the variable options for the categorical values, so there are only 4 genres and 4 publishers. I chose these 4 options based on the amount of observations linked to each one so I chose the 4 most popular options in the entire data set. I used Zenodo which got the data off of vgchartz.com, a website that tracks various trends and information about video games. This data was collected from vgchartz.com website in 2022. Link: https://zenodo.org/records/5898311

Id like to answer how big of a different are the sales in games for European gamers compared to North American gamers? as well as Which publisher has taken over many of the gaming platforms?.

Wii Sports from Wikipedia (https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wii_Sports)

Data Preparation

## Warning: Unknown or uninitialised column: `CompanyOrigin`.

The website Zenodo scraped the data from vgchartz.com and put it in a csv file so I was able to quickly import it into RStudio. One of the challenges I faced was that many of the categorical variables had 10+ options so I used a table to find the most popular options and used the top 4. After all the filtering to meet the requirements, the data observations went from 20k+ to 1600.

Variable Descriptions

Name Type Discription
Rank double Ranking of overall sales
Name character The games name
Platform character Platform of the games release
Year character Year of the games release
Genre character Genre of the game
Publisher character Publisher of the game
NA_Sales double Sales in North America (in millions)
EU_Sales double Sales in Europe (in millions)
JP_Sales double Sales in Japan (in millions)
Other_Sales double Sales in the rest of the world (in millions)
Global_Sales double Total worldwide sales(in millions)
Age double How old the game is in 2025
CompanyOrigin character Company Origin

Bivariate Analyses:

European Sales of Games Versus North American Sales

The graph of European Sales versus North American Sales of video games has a moderate positive correlation and an correlation coefficient of 0.48. As the European sales increase, the American sales also increase.

Rank Versus Global Sales

The graph of Rank versus Global Sales of video games has a moderate negative correlation and an correlation coefficient of -0.64. As the European sales increase, the American sales also increase.

Age Versus Global Sales

The graph of Age versus Global Sales of video games has a very weak postive correlation and an correlation coefficient of 0.06. As the age increases, the global sales increase.

Choice Elements:

I created two new variables (age and company origin) by subtracting the year it was released to 2025 as well as googling the company origin of the publishers. I also parsed the string variable Year into a number for the age variable. I added a floating table of contents to the top left. I also added 5 or more in-line codes in my report as the descriptions of the graphs have a in line numeric values. I made the graph section titles smaller than the main section titles so that on the table of contents, it allows user to go to the main section and the subsections. I have changed the font style, size, and color.

Conclusion:

Answering my 1st research question, there isnt too large of a different because as European gamers buy games, North American gamers are also buying games. For my second question, EA has the most games on PlayStation but Sony only has games on PlayStation. EA has the most games on all platforms. I have also noticed that the genre with the most games is sports games while the genre with the least is role-playing games. The median age for a video game in the data set is 17 years with an IQR of 7 years. One future area of research could be finding player counts within the first year because many games could have high sales but differing player counts or average player game time.
